VALUES
(42, 24, 6, 40, 17, 22, 23, NULL, 'Resurrection Prediction Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the prediction of Jesus'' resurrection. In Luke, the angel reminds the disciples of Jesus'' words about rising, while Matthew records Jesus stating he would be raised on the third day.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 6, 42, 9, 22, 22, 'is risen', 'Resurrection Prophecy Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus. Luke 24:6 refers to His rising, while Luke 9:22 predicts His resurrection on the third day.', 'prophecy', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 6, 41, 8, 31, 31, NULL, 'Resurrection Prediction Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus. Luke 24:6 recalls Jesus'' prediction of rising after death, which is explicitly stated in Mark 8:31.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 6, 40, 28, 6, 6, 'He is not here, but is risen', 'Resurrection Announcement Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus, stating ''He is not here'' and affirming that he has risen. This connection highlights the shared message of the angelic announcement to the women at the tomb.', 'parallel', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 6, 41, 10, 33, 34, NULL, 'Resurrection Prediction Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Jesus. Luke 24:6 states, ''He is not here, but is risen,'' while Mark 10:34 predicts, ''the third day he shall rise again.'' This connection highlights the fulfillment of Jesus'' prophecy about his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 6, 42, 9, 44, 44, 'He is not here, but is risen', 'Connection of Resurrection and Prophecy', 'This connection highlights the prophecy of Jesus'' resurrection. Both passages emphasize the foretelling of his deliverance and subsequent rising.', 'prophecy', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 7, 40, 16, 21, 21, 'the third day rise again', 'Connection of Jesus'' Suffering and Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of Jesus'' suffering, death, and resurrection on the third day. They highlight the same sequence of events regarding his fate, indicating a shared understanding of his mission.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 8, 43, 12, 16, 16, 'And they remembered his words,', 'Memory of Jesus'' Words', 'Both passages emphasize the act of remembering Jesus'' words in relation to understanding his significance. In Luke, the disciples remember his words after his resurrection, while in John, they recall these things after Jesus is glorified.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 8, 43, 14, 26, 26, 'they remembered his words', 'Remembrance and Teaching Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of remembrance in both passages. In Luke, the phrase ''they remembered his words'' emphasizes recalling Jesus'' teachings, while John speaks of the Holy Spirit bringing ''all things to your remembrance,'' suggesting a divine aid in remembering Jesus'' words.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 8, 43, 2, 19, 22, 'And they remembered his words', 'Disciples Remembering Jesus'' Words', 'This connection highlights the theme of remembrance in both passages. In Luke, the disciples remember Jesus'' words after his resurrection, while in John, they recall his statement about the temple after he rises from the dead.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 9, 40, 28, 7, 8, 'told all these things unto the eleven', 'Resurrection Announcement Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of telling the disciples about Jesus'' resurrection. The women in Luke return to inform the eleven, paralleling the directive in Matthew to go and tell the disciples.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 9, 41, 16, 7, 8, 'told all these things unto the eleven', 'Resurrection Announcement Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of telling the disciples about the resurrection. In Luke, the women return to share the news, while Mark instructs them to tell the disciples and Peter.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 9, 42, 24, 22, 24, 'returned from the sepulchre', 'Women at the Sepulchre', 'This connection highlights the role of women in the resurrection narrative. Both passages mention the women returning from the sepulchre and sharing their experiences, emphasizing their astonishment and the message of the angels.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 9, 41, 16, 10, 10, 'told all these things unto the eleven', 'Women as Messengers of Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of women in delivering the news of Jesus'' resurrection to the disciples. In Luke, the women return from the sepulchre to tell the eleven, while in Mark, one woman tells those who mourned and wept.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 10, 40, 27, 56, 56, 'Mary the mother of James', 'Women Witnesses in Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Mary Magdalene and Mary the mother of James. This connection highlights the role of these women in significant events surrounding Jesus'' death and resurrection.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 10, 41, 15, 40, 41, NULL, 'Women Witnesses of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of women, particularly Mary Magdalene and Mary the mother of James, in significant moments of Jesus'' ministry and resurrection. This connection highlights their role as witnesses and supporters of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 10, 41, 16, 9, 11, 'which told these things unto the apostles', 'Women as Witnesses of Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Mary Magdalene and other women in proclaiming the resurrection of Jesus. They highlight the women''s testimony to the apostles, underscoring their significance in the resurrection narrative.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 10, 42, 8, 2, 3, 'Mary Magdalene, and Joanna', 'Women in Jesus'' Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the role of women in Jesus'' ministry. The women mentioned in Luke 24:10, including Mary Magdalene and Joanna, are connected to their earlier support of Jesus in Luke 8:2-3.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 10, 43, 20, 11, 18, 'which told these things unto the apostles', 'Women as Messengers of Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Mary Magdalene in proclaiming the resurrection of Jesus. In Luke, she is among the women who tell the apostles about the resurrection, while in John, she directly encounters the risen Jesus and informs the disciples of her experience.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 11, 18, 9, 16, 16, 'believed them not', 'Skepticism in Response to Revelation', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief in divine communication. Both passages emphasize a reluctance to accept messages perceived as incredible or untrustworthy.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 11, 41, 16, 11, 11, 'believed them not', 'Disbelief in Resurrection Accounts', 'Both passages emphasize disbelief regarding the resurrection. In Luke, the words seemed as idle tales, while in Mark, they believed not after hearing of His appearance.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 11, 1, 19, 14, 14, NULL, 'Rejection of Urgent Warnings', 'Both passages emphasize the disbelief of urgent warnings. In Luke, the disciples dismiss the resurrection news as ''idle tales,'' while in Genesis, Lot''s warning is seen as mockery by his sons-in-law.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 11, 19, 126, 1, 1, 'idle tales', 'Dreams and Belief in God', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief in miraculous events. In Luke, the disciples dismiss the resurrection as ''idle tales,'' while Psalms speaks of a transformative experience that feels dreamlike. Both passages emphasize a contrast between skepticism and divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 11, 12, 7, 2, 2, 'believed them not', 'Skepticism and Divine Assurance', 'Both passages emphasize disbelief in God''s promises. In Luke, the disciples dismiss the resurrection as ''idle tales,'' while in 2 Kings, the lord questions God''s ability to provide. This connection highlights the theme of skepticism towards divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 11, 42, 24, 25, 25, 'believed them not', 'Belief and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief in the resurrection. Both passages emphasize the need for faith in the words of the prophets, contrasting the initial skepticism of the disciples.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 11, 44, 12, 9, 9, 'believed them not', 'Skepticism of the Supernatural', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief in miraculous events. Both passages emphasize a lack of faith in what is perceived as extraordinary, with characters questioning the reality of their experiences.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 12, 43, 20, 3, 10, 'linen clothes laid by themselves', 'Discovery of the Empty Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s visit to the sepulchre and his observation of the linen clothes. They detail the sequence of events as Peter and the other disciple investigate the empty tomb, highlighting their wonder and belief.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 13, 41, 16, 12, 13, 'two of them went that same day', 'Connection of the Emmaus Journey', 'Both passages emphasize the journey of two individuals after the resurrection. In Luke, they are going to Emmaus, while in Mark, they are described as walking into the country, highlighting their shared experience of encountering the risen Christ.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 13, 42, 24, 18, 18, 'two of them', 'Connection of Journey to Emmaus', 'Both passages emphasize the journey of two individuals from Jerusalem to Emmaus. The mention of ''two of them'' in the source verse connects directly to Cleopas, one of the travelers, in the target passage.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 24, 14, 5, 6, 7, 7, 'talked together of all these things', 'Teaching and Discussion of Events', 'This connection highlights the importance of discussing significant events and teachings. Both passages emphasize the act of talking about important matters, whether it be the events of Jesus'' life or the commandments given to children.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
